title: 90% of my peers are more than 100 block behind the latest block !

body: Could you share your methodology for retrieving the number?

If you're using `admin.peers` and retrieving the head, I guess that's problematic after the merge. The merge disabled block propagation / announcements, so that number will never be updated. It will be the one seen during handshake and will remain as is.
Yeah... Should we somehow improve it? Perhaps hide the block number seems it's meaningless anyway, or start a pingpong to retrieve the head from peers periodically.

>  Perhaps hide the block number seems it's meaningless anyway, or start a pingpong to retrieve the head from peers periodically.

Hiding it feels wrong to me, and retrieving it from time to time also seems silly, since it's not info that we need. IMO let's leave it as it is

damn, that whas my main selection system to have clean updated peers.

how can i improve my peers, and be sure i don't have bad/slow peers based on admin.peers data ? drop peers with old geth version maybe ?
Ok, the decision was to remove this information from the APIs from now on. There's no point to display something out of date.

> how can i improve my peers, and be sure i don't have bad/slow peers based on admin.peers data ? drop peers with old geth version maybe ?

Why do you feel the need to improve your peers? During initial sync, Geth will actually drop slow peers that might serve data at a lower rate than we can consume it. However, after initial sync, there's no big data transfer happening any more, why drop slower peers?
